Electrical Connector (Avionics Component) - Cleaning

ATA Chapter (Illustrative): 20 — Standard Practices (as cleaning procedures for electrical components are often standardized) or could be system-specific if unique (e.g., 24-XX-XX for an electrical power system connector).
S1000D DMC (Illustrative and Generic): XXXXXX-A-20-11-03-00A-650A-A
Aircraft/Company: Not Specified / Generic Manufacturer


This task involves:

    - Ensuring all related electrical power to the component and connector is OFF and safetied.
    - Implementing Electrostatic Discharge (ESD) protection measures.
    - Gaining access to the specified electrical connector.
    - Carefully disconnecting the connector halves (if required for thorough cleaning and if permitted by maintenance philosophy).
    - Applying approved cleaning agents using specified tools (e.g., non-metallic brushes, lint-free swabs) to remove contaminants from connector pins, sockets, and shell.
    - Using low-pressure, dry, filtered air for drying or removing loose particles.
    - Visually inspecting the cleaned connector for any remaining contamination, damage (bent pins, cracked insulation), or corrosion.
    - Reconnecting the connector (if disconnected), ensuring proper alignment and mating.
    - Verifying electrical bonding of the connector shell (if applicable) after reconnection.


